dataIdInfo.idAbs: Annual Five-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for 2015 to 2030 for the national, and first- and second-order administrative division levels of Namibia were prepared by the U.S. Census Bureau for joining (linking) to shapefiles as attribute data. The estimates are consistent with the midyear national projections from the U.S. Census Bureau International Data Base (IDB).
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The U.S. Census Bureau is providing annual subnational five-year age group population estimates by sex for Namibia for 2015-2030 in a geographic information system (GIS) for users of the Spatial Data Repository, funded by the U.S. President’s Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR).
dataIdInfo.idCredit:
CENSUS DATA 2011 Age-Sex Data: 2011 Population and Housing Census Main Report, Table 2.2 Population Distribution by Age Group and Sex. Namibia Statistics Agency. Available online at http://cms.my.na/assets/documents/p19dmn0tnha6gcqq1s9g116e1uk01.pdf (Table 2.2 for each region is followed by tables for each of its constituencies, accessed January 11, 2022).
2001 Population Total Data: 2001 Population and Housing Census Regional Profiles, Table 1.2.1 Population Distribution by Sex and Area. Namibia Statistics Agency. Available online at http://nsa.org.na/page/publications/ (PDFs for each region must be downloaded individually, accessed January 11, 2022).
The U.S. Census Bureau cannot guarantee the accuracy of non-U.S. census and survey data.
GEOSPATIAL BOUNDARIES International boundaries coincide with the Large Scale International Boundaries (LSIB) dataset from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues. Available online at http://geonode.state.gov (accessed January 14, 2022).
Geospatial data for the second-order administrative divisions of Namibia were downloaded from the Humanitarian Data Exchange, available online at http://data.humdata.org/dataset/namibia-admin-level-1-boundaries, "Namibia - Subnational Administrative Boundaries" (accessed January 07, 2022).
The U.S. Census Bureau cannot guarantee the accuracy of boundary placements.
NATIONAL ESTIMATES AND PROJECTIONS U.S. Census Bureau, Population Division. International Data Base, December 2021 release, available online at http://www.census.gov/data-tools/demo/idb/ (accessed January 11, 2022).
NATIONAL AND SUBNATIONAL AREA NAMES AND CODES (1) U.S. National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency. NGA GEOnet Names Server (GNS), available at http://geonames.nga.mil/gns/html/ (accessed January 14, 2022). Contains geographic area names from the U.S. Board on Geographic Names and the U.S. Government Federal Information Processing System (FIPS) codes. (2) U.S. Government Geopolitical Entities, Names, and Codes (GENC) Standard. NSG Standards Registry, available at http://nsgreg.nga.mil/genc/discovery (accessed January 14, 2022).

dataIdInfo.suppInfo:
SUBNATIONAL DIVISIONS Namibia's second-order administrative divisions: 107 constituencies as of the 2011 census.
SHAPEFILES The original shapefile downloaded from the Humanitarian Data Exchange had 107 polygons and matched the 2011 census constituencies (second-order administrative divisions) with no changes to the subnational boundaries made by USCB staff. The U.S. Census Bureau aligned the shapefile's national boundary to the Large Scale International Boundary Line (LSIB) polygon file from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues.
CENSUS DATA INTERPOLATION The 2001 census totals had the following differences in geography that have been modified to their 2011 locations in the estimates presented here, requiring interpolation and adjustment of 2001 population data by USCB staff: (1) A number of constituencies split off to form new areas between the 2001 and 2011 censuses or had significant boundary changes, as noted in the "USCBCMNT" field, requiring interpolation and adjustment of 2001 population data by U.S. Census Bureau staff.
For new constituencies that were fully formed from part of a single area, where boundaries and population data were not available for the next administrative level down, the total population of the original area in 2001 was divided proportionally according to the populations of the new areas in 2011. For new constituencies that were formed from parts of multiple original areas, where boundaries and population data were not available for the next administrative level down, the total population of the new area in 2011 was divided proportionally according to the land areas of the multiple original pieces in square kilometers.
FEATURE AND ATTRIBUTE DETAILS The 2015-2030 population estimates for Namibia's administrative divisions are provided in the following two tables: (1) The Unicode tab-delimited text file (table) "Namibia_5yr_age_sex_2015-2030_uscb_mar2022.txt," which can be joined to the shapefile via the common field "GEO_MATCH." (2) The Excel table "Namibia_5yr_age_sex_2015-2030_508_uscb_mar2022.xlsx," formatted for accessibility in compliance with Section 508 of the U.S. Government's Federal Rehabilitation Act.
Details on processing of the census data and calculation of 2015-2030 estimates are provided in the "Census Metadata" tab of the Excel file and "Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas" document. For the subnational areas, the U.S. Board on Geographic Names (BGN) "approved" names from the NGA GEOnet Names Server (cited in the "Credits") were used. For any area that a BGN name was not available, the name from the national census was used. Official codes for the subnational areas from the country's national statistical office, when available, are entered in the "NSO_CODE" field in both the text and Excel tables. Information on any alternative area names or recent name or boundary changes is entered in the "USCBCMNT" field. A partial list of the fields in the Excel and Unicode text files, including all fields identifying geographic names and codes, is provided in the Excel file's "Data Dictionary" tab. More detail on the U.S. Census Bureau subnational age and sex group estimates and maps for PEPFAR can be found in the document "Subnational Population Estimates Components for the Spatial Data Repository." It includes a data dictionary that is similar to that in the Excel table.
METHODOLOGY For more information, see the following methodology documents in the Spatial Data Repository: (1) "U.S. Census Bureau Methodology for SDR Subnational Population Estimates." (2) "U.S. Census Bureau Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas." (3) "Instructions for Joining Subnational Population Data to Shapefiles."
ACCESS The U.S. Census Bureau’s products for PEPFAR can be accessed from the Spatial Data Repository at http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/home/, which also provides access to data and maps from the DHS (Demographic and Health Surveys) Program. A zipped file containing shapefiles with metadata, an Excel workbook with subnational population estimates, and a Unicode tab-delimited text file is available for each country. PEPFAR products are also available on the Census Bureau website at http://www.census.gov/geographies/mapping-files/time-series/demo/international-programs/subnationalpopulation.html for download.
